    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-12-04T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-12-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="414"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d414">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName> Papers: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The President’s Secretary</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_ES1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Early</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the President’s Special Assistant</hi>
                        (<persName corresp="#p_HHL1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hopkins</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="1" xml:id="d414fn1">Presumably sent via military
                        channels.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-12-04">4 December
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>For Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HHL1">Hopkins</persName> from Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_ES1">Early</persName>.</p>
                <p>All press and radio here headline today Moscow radio reports received via London
                    that <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName>, <persName
                        corresp="#p_CC2">Churchill</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_SIV1"
                        >Stalin</persName> had met in Teheran few days ago and discussed questions
                    related to war against Germany and including political war issues. The reports
                    added that the conferences have been concluded and detailed statement is
                    expected momentarily. This comes from the government controlled Moscow radio and
                    further complicates the situation resulting from the British Reuters premature
                    disclosures concerning Cairo conference.<note n="2" xml:id="d414fn2">See
                            <persName corresp="#p_DE1">Davis</persName>’ message of November 30,
                        1943, to <persName corresp="#p_BB1">Bracken</persName>, <hi rend="italic"
                            >ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_452">p. 452</ref>.</note> If mechanically
                    possible and in face of these developments, I urge quickest possible release and
                    publication of Teheran communiqué. Regards.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
